<br>
I have also been poking about the nozzle problem.  Hmmm.  That's another area that's gonna be fun.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
But first, questions:<br>
<br>
whitestar60: <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> I was just wondering, how exactly does the fuel system for the engine work, and (seince no one else asked) please describe the fuel cycle for the rocket. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Actually, I already posted this earlier.  After nobody asked for a while, I just went ahead and put it in.<br>
<br>
In a nutshell, each thruster has a fuel vault made of boron/aluminum tubing.  The internal volume of the fuel vault is few dozen cubic meters, consisting of thickwalled tubes of small internal diameter so that a critical mass is impossible to assemble inside the vault.<br>
<br>
The vault has electrical heating wires on it, and has provisions for hydrogen gas from the main fuel tank to be vented across the outside of the tubing.  There is a small amount of helium provided as well to be used as flush gas.<br>
<br>
The reason for this is due to the physical properties of uranium hexaflouride, which can be easily converted from high pressure gas to nearly zero pressure solids simply by cooling it, and can be converted back simply by heating it.<br>
<br>
The fuel vault is divided into 4 sections, acsent fresh fuel, ascent spent fuel, descent fresh fuel, and descent spent fuel.  Shortly before launch, a fuel truck pumps the ascent sections of the vault full of warm liquid UF6, which is composed of 20 percent U235.  These sections are actually very small, say a volume of 50 liters.<br>
<br>
The cooled UF6 is kept here until late in the countdown, when ascent phase section is heated to high temperature, making it gaseous and raising the presure to 1500 psi or so.  From here, the UF6 is injected slowly into the lightbulb along with control jets of buffer gas until the core goes critical.   As the ship flies to orbit, more UF6 is tapped from this ascent phase store if/as needed.<br>
<br>
Once the thruster has finished its work, the ascent phase spent fuel vault is called to duty.<br>
<br>
This section is MUCH larger, and is kept in a vacuum.  As the thrusters are shut down, the gas jets are used to scramble the core vortex, killing the reaction by dropping the density of the uranium in the core far under criticality.  The core is allowed to cool for a few minutes, then the hot and VERY radioactive expended UF6 is &quot;vacuumed&quot; into the large spent fuel vault by the simple method of opening a valve.  As the hot UF6 rushes in, the vault is sprayed with cold hydrogen gas, dropping the temperature and pressure dramatically, and causing the UF6 in the vault to solidify.  The vapor pressure of UF6 is very low, so as it solidifies the vacuum of the vault is preserved so that the entire volume of the lightbulb can be effectively sucked into the vault without having to resort to a pump!<br>
<br>
(I love passive systems.  It's hard to break a simple hydrogen valve and a resistance wire.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    )<br>
<br>
After a few minutes, the large ascent/spent vault is heated with a wire to gassify the radioactive spent UF6.  More valves open to plumb the six outside vaults to the vault on the center thruster, and as the Liberty Ship performs its orbital circularization burn, the radioactive UF6 is vented into the reaction chamber of the center engine and blasted into deep space, with the help of a hearty blast of helium flush gas.<br>
<br>
Now, I feel certain the energy and density of the radioactive plume will zip through the Earths radiation belts and out into space.  By timing the burn, we can dump the waste where we want it, either into deep space or into the Sun.<br>
<br>
After the circularization burn, the last thruster dumps its spent fuel into all seven ascent phase spent vaults, driving the material to deep non-criticality and letting the boron in the tubing do its work mopping up those nasty neutrons.<br>
<br>
When the Liberty Ship re-enters, the descent phase fresh fuel vault, another small section, injects a fresh dose of new fuel into the thrusters, the LibertyShip flies back down under power, and lands.  Upon landing, the spent UF6 is vacuumed into the last, large section of the fuel vault, the descent phase spent fuel vault for storage until the next flight.<br>
<br>
If the next flight is a long time away, the spent UF6 can be heated up and dumped into terrestrial storage.<br>
<br>
On the second flight of the Liberty Ship, the spent fuel from the descent phase of the first flght is put back on, up it flies, and gets dumped along with the spent fuel generated by that flights ascent phase.<br>
<br>
Over time, the Liberty Ship disposes of all of its waste.  If we decide to use the system as such, we can also load up high level wastes generated by terrestrial sources and get rid of it permanently.  <br>
<br>
So, the Liberty Ship can be used to permanently and completely dispose of high level nuclear wastes, including its own.<br>
<br>
What's not to love?  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> <br>
How thick are the walls of the glass bulb?  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I don't know!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
That is the sort of thing that would require HUGE amounts of modeling to know for certain.  I can make a guess or two, however.<br>
<br>
It seems obvious there are competing issues here.  From a physical durability standpoint, thicker is better.  From a thermal/neutron standpoint, thinner is better.  <br>
<br>
There will be some point, determined by the exact properties of the bulb and the exact operating conditions of the thruster, that is optimum.  I suspect it will be somewhere between 3 and 10 centimeters of silica, probably in at least three and maybe 5 layers, with the layers seperated by blown-in expandable foam until launch.<br>
<br>
Plus, there may be deliberate ablative layers of the lightbulb added to either the inside or the outside, &quot;sacrificial&quot; layers designed to erode away during flight.  I don't think they will be needed given the transmissivity we can give that bulb these days, but it is nice to know the option is there.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Hmm, sounds like a good idea, though the thought of containing a very hot nuclear reaction, using Uranium hexafloride, in what is essentialy a glass jar. A high tech jar, but still a jar non the less. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Ok, this is a common misconception.  Let me see if I can explain.<br>
<br>
The silica envelope only serves as a seal, to prevent mixing of gases between the reactor vortex and the fuel vortex.  In a properly designed GCNR, the lightbulb will not have to withstand any but the lowest PHYSICAL stresses.  <br>
<br>
What is containing the nuclear reaction is the VORTEX of gas.  This is similar to how a poached egg is cooked.  You stir a pot of water very fast until a whirlpool forms (the vortex) then crack the egg down into the vortex and cook it.  The same theory applies here.  The supercritical uranium core is the &quot;egg&quot; and the buffer gas is the water.  The amount of energy in the buffer gas, the &quot;vorticity,&quot; determines the strength of the containment.  The silica bulb just keeps the vortex from leaking.<br>
<br>
Does that make more sense now?  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> I would be a little nervous watching a launch. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
LOL!  You'd have to have a good ship to see a launch, since I want to light this puppy up WAY out in the middle of the Pacific ocean at Baker Island.  <br>
<br>
Also, due to the MUCH higher power levels of the Liberty Ship than I thought (dopey me!) I have decided that the launch vessel will have to be a semi-submersible design.  At launch, the Liberty Ship will be expending 540 Gigawatts of waste energy.  I would not trust a water spray system to deal with that, so I'll just put the launch ship under 20 feet of water and launch the Liberty Ship off pylons.  <br>
<br>
Also, the neutron flux from a Liberty Ship is not something I would want to be within a few kilometers of, unless I had a thick layer of shielding in the way.  Like a few meters of water.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
