omWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=76>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Possible source for design answers.</span><hr size=1> The paper was presented in the Twelth Symposium on Space Nuclear Power and Propulsion by the American Institute of Physics. See if you can get ahold of the conference proceedings through interlibrary loan.<br>
<br>
First a few notes on the design as you have it pictured in the diagram. For the inert buffer gas Argon was used in most examples, so it should be a good choice. And you will need to add a neutron moderator. U-235 is very bad at absorbing fast neutrons, a lighter Z material like carbon or hydrogen would be much better. One of the sites I linked to had a graphite moderator. I would suggest adding one, I am not sure the design will go or remain critical without it.<br>
<br>
One problem you have to deal with is that the hotter the core is the higher energy the photons escaping being radiated from it, the opacity of the U gas actually decreases. NLBs run at the far end of the UV transmission capibilities of silica. Running the core at extreme temperatures means having to deal with increased absorbed fraction of the radiatice flux. At 50000K ultra-pure full-spectrum silica absorbs 87.5% of the radiant energy. Running the core at 20000K reduces this to 36.2%, and 14000K at 13.6%. Luckily internaly coolong the thin wall can allow you still run it fairly hot. Temperatures in the 15000K-25000K are probibly feaisible  with modern technology (they were seen as a stretch in the report, but I'm optomistic). Running the wall at 25000K requires 35kg/s*m^2 of internal (H2) coolant, 20000K requires only 14kg/s*m^2 (50000K requires 384kg/s*m^2!). Because the silica buble is so thin (I am not sure what effects thickening it consieribly would do, complex systems are difficult to predict), you can only flow so much internal coolant before the preasure shears the containment vessel. Due to this restriction the authors felt that running the core any hotter then 25000K is essentialy impossible. The 50000K levels you have seen are probibly for open core designs.<br>
<br>
20000-25000K is still pretty darn hot, over 8 times the temperature of a SCNR. It will probibly require more mass being assigned to engines, although I am not sure how much more. <p>&quot;If,&quot; he wispered, &quot;if we could only pick that lock....&quot; - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mylenejenius@nuclearspace>MyleneJenius</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 41<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/26/02 9:15:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=77>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.csclub.uwaterloo.ca/u/yhchan/gallery/mylene/thumbnail/Mac704.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Possible source for design answers.</span><hr size=1> Ok... initial results of the Orbiter simulation of the Liberty Ship has shown that it guzzles alot more fuel than I think any of us figured it would. I can sit there and watch the fuel gauge go down. I think it is going to need more fuel and lighter weight construction than previously thought. Or the design may need its thrust downtuned to say about 1 million pounds of thrust even to try to get the fuel consumption to a reasonable level. I think the payload may need to be reduced by about 25-50% and more fuel added. And weight really needs to be cut as much as possible. Don't shoot me... I'm just reporting the flight simulation results.<br>
