Oh, and one last tidbit is this .pdf:  <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.llnl.gov/etr/pdfs/03_95.2.pdf"> www.llnl.gov/etr/pdfs/03_95.2.pdf </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
For the Liberty Ship lightbulb, we only need silica to transmit wavelengths down to about 190nm.  In that .pdf they are making working mirrors and beam splitters for X-RAY LASERS out of our friendly wonder material, silica, way, way down at 40nm and under.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :eek --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/eek.gif ALT=":eek"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
Yeah, I think we can beat the transmission issues for the lightbulb these days.<br>
<br>
Plus, these guys state they have silica based mirrors for 15nm X-rays that have reflectance values of 60 percent.  Holy COW.<br>
